        <h1>Welcome to The Fortress!</h1>
        <h3>What is this site about?</h3>
        <p>The Fortress is a proof-of-concept secure website.  If the data concerned real people, it would be considered Personally Identifiable Information - PII.  Such data is a target for criminals, and a priority for owners to protect.  Of course, the "staff" in this database are entirely fictional, and therefore useless to the criminal.  The data is a goal for the site to defend, and therefore it is also the objective for anyone testing the site.</p>
        <p><strong>This is not a Capture-The-Flag cybergame. </strong>A CTF site has specific vulnerabilities included for people learning to run security tests, and perhaps available to curious amatures who want to try their knowledge of hacking without breaking the law.  Several such games exist, including National Cyber League and SANS.ORG Netwars challenges.  The Fortress did not leave vulnerabilities intentionally, and therefore it is far more difficult to hack then a CTF.</p>
        <p>What The Fortress has in common with CTF games is that it is legal to attack - if you follow the rules.  Ethical hackers work within a contractual scope when running security tests.  This challenge doesn't have a written contract, but there are still rules of ethical hacking that apply.  More details is on the Rules page.</p>
    </aside>
